A Dockerfile is a plain text file that contains a set of instructions Docker uses to build a custom image. Think of it as a recipe â€” it tells Docker exactly what to install, copy, and configure inside the image.

ğŸ“„ ğ—˜ğ˜…ğ—®ğ—ºğ—½ğ—¹ğ—²: ğ—” ğ—¦ğ—¶ğ—ºğ—½ğ—¹ğ—² ğ——ğ—¼ğ—°ğ—¸ğ—²ğ—¿ğ—³ğ—¶ğ—¹ğ—² ğ—³ğ—¼ğ—¿ ğ—® ğ—£ğ˜†ğ˜ğ—µğ—¼ğ—» ğ—”ğ—½ğ—½
Letâ€™s say you have a small Python app (app.py). Your Dockerfile might look like this:
---
# Use an official Python runtime as a base image
FROM python:3.11-slim

# Set the working directory in the container
WORKDIR /app

# Copy the local code to the container
COPY app.py .

# Run the Python app
CMD ["python", "app.py"]
---
ğŸ§ª ğ—•ğ˜‚ğ—¶ğ—¹ğ—± ğ˜ğ—µğ—² ğ—œğ—ºğ—®ğ—´ğ—²
To build an image from this Dockerfile, run:

$ docker build -t my-python-app .
 â€¢ -t: Tags the image with a name
 â€¢ . : Specifies the current directory (where Dockerfile resides)

This command reads the Dockerfile, executes each instruction, and creates a new image called my-python-app.

